Step 1. Calculate Debt to Equity Ratio  
• From the balance sheet, the only liability is from taxes payable (since accounts payable is 0).  
 Total Liabilities = 1,015,922.54  
 Total Owner's Equity = 29,842,166.21  
• Debt to Equity Ratio = Total Liabilities / Total Owner's Equity = 1,015,922.54 / 29,842,166.21 ≈ 0.034 → Rounded to two decimals: 0.03  

Step 2. Calculate Net Profit Margin  
• From the income statement,  
 Net Profit = 1,842,166.21  
 Total Revenue = 20,318,450.67  
• Net Profit Margin = Net Profit / Total Revenue = 1,842,166.21 / 20,318,450.67 ≈ 0.09066 = 9.07%  

Step 3. Calculate Return on Assets (ROA)  
• Total Assets from the balance sheet = 30,858,088.75  
• ROA = Net Profit / Total Assets = 1,842,166.21 / 30,858,088.75 ≈ 0.05967 = 5.97%  

Step 4. Calculate Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
• Accounts Receivable at the end is 12,792,007.89 and initial value is 0, so the average accounts receivable = (0 + 12,792,007.89) / 2 = 6,396,003.945  
• Using Total Revenue as the numerator (assuming credit sales approximates revenue),  
 Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio = Total Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable = 20,318,450.67 / 6,396,003.945 ≈ 3.177 → Rounded to two decimals: 3.18  

Thus, the final solution is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.03",
    "Net Profit Margin": "9.07%",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "5.97%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "3.18"
  }
}
